body:
@mfuntowicz,  the function name was changed to change_graph_inputs_to_int32() in 1.9.0 (see https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8927), could you double check that you are using 1.9.0 (You might need uninstall nightly package first).

If 1.9.0 has the problem, could you also try our nightly package 'https://test.pypi.org/project/ort-nightly/'. Let me know if it still have issue.

Hi @tianleiwu, 

Thanks for the update.

I did see the name change and tried both versions with different outcomes, but both were failing.
I will rerun the test with the correct 1.9 API, also testing out nightly and will report here.

ðŸ™ðŸ»

@tianleiwu just tested with the correct method call: 

```python

optimization_options = FusionOptions("bert")
optimization_options.enable_embed_layer_norm = True

optimized_graph = optimize_model(
    input=model_path.as_posix(),
    model_type=export_config.topology.onnx.optimizer,
    num_heads=model_config.num_attention_heads,
    hidden_size=model_config.hidden_size,
    opt_level=export_config.topology.onnx.optimization_level,
    use_gpu=export_config.hardware.kind == HardwareKind.GPU,
    optimization_options=optimization_options,
)

optimized_graph.change_graph_inputs_to_int32()
...

# Error happens here when trying to save the model, 
optimized_graph.save_model_to_file(
    optimized_model_path.as_posix(), use_external_data_format=use_external_data_format
)
```


Output: 

```
  File "python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/transformers/onnx_model.py", line 868, in save_model_to_file
    self.topological_sort()

    OnnxModel.graph_topological_sort(self.model.graph)

```

Is there anything I should try?

@tianleiwu I just tested with a fresh build from master branch and these 3 models are crashing with the above assertion.

```python
assert (end == len(graph.node)), "Graph is not a DAG"
AssertionError: Graph is not a DAG
```

I'm digging a bit to see if I can spot anything. Will report here if I find anything.

Ok, dig a little bit more, I'm not sure but it seems some depdencies are not visited through the topological sort: 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2241520/140158288-58860912-b061-41da-b8cd-6f2b44c40ede.png)

And the following check: 

```python
assert (end == len(graph.node)), "Graph is not a DAG"
```

fails because `end=60` and `len(graph.node) = 65`.

Then if you look at the `deps_count`  list debugger view above, you see 5 nodes still have dependencies which haven't been visited, thus leading to the assertion being trigged.

@mfuntowicz. The error usually means that the graph is invalid. If you save the model without topological sort, you might observe graph is not DAG. Could you share the ONNX if you cannot resolve it by upgrading packages?

I did not reproduce the issue with master branch in Window. Steps I used:
```
python tools\ci_build\build.py --config Debug --build_dir build/Cpu_Debug --build_shared_lib --cmake_generator "Visual Studio 16 2019" --build_wheel --skip_tests

pip install build\Cpu_Debug\Debug\Debug\dist\onnxruntime-1.10.0-cp36-cp36m-win_amd64.whl --force-reinstall

python -m transformers.onnx -m sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2 --opset 12 --feature default .

python test.py
```

The content of test.py:
```
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModel
from onnxruntime.transformers.optimizer import optimize_model
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2')

model = AutoModel.from_pretrained('sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2')
model_config = model.config

from onnxruntime.transformers.fusion_options import FusionOptions
optimization_options = FusionOptions("bert")

optimized_graph = optimize_model(
    input="model.onnx",
    model_type="bert",
    num_heads=model_config.num_attention_heads,
    hidden_size=model_config.hidden_size,
    opt_level=99,
    use_gpu=True,
    optimization_options=optimization_options,
)

optimized_graph.convert_float_to_float16(keep_io_types=True)
optimized_graph.change_graph_inputs_to_int32()
optimized_graph.save_model_to_file(
     "model_opt.onnx", use_external_data_format=False,
)
```

In my machine, the optimized model was generated correctly. My environment is like the following (from `python -m onnxruntime.transformers.machine_info`)
```

  },
```
Thanks @tianleiwu I will test with the same setup than you reported and post the results here ðŸ™ðŸ»
